T2

Yes indeedy! Today was the first day this film was being shown in 
England so I thought I'd nip down the cinema with Raphael and 
have a butchers. We arrived at the place 40 minutes early (!!) 
and the queue wasn't too long then. Infact by the time we were 
let in (five minutes early!!!!!) the queue was still suprisingly 
quite short. I think alot of people had thought that it would be 
very crowded on the first day and so did not turn up, but because 
so many people didn't turn up there was hardly any one there 
(makes sense really). So, we waited for 40 minutes in the intense 
heat for nothing.
  I was in two minds about a sequel to the film Terminator. As 
you will know if you've seen this film (who hasn't?) it is bloody 
excellent and by the end of the film you are thinking "I'd like 
to see some more of that, hope they make a sequel". However as I 
queued up outside the cinema I was having second thoughts. A 
sequel is never as good as the original film, even when the first 
film was crap, and seeing as The Terminator was one of the best 
films ever made I knew these guys really had there work cut out 
to make something that was even remotely as good as the first. 
  If you haven't seen T2 (which you probably will have by the 
time you read this) you will still know that is cost 100 million 
to make, and that the special FX are some of the best you are 
likely to see in any film this decade. What I was afriad off was 
that they would spend so much of FX that some how they would 
forget about a story line.
  You should also know that in the sequel, Arnie is the good guy, 
unlike in the original. Knowing this before you see the film does 
rather spoil the first 10-20 mins of the film. You see when the 
two guys materialise, because arnie was the baddy in the first, 
and is also much bigger and stronger than the other dude, you 
think that he is still the bad guy and that the other bloke is 
another normal human who will try and save Sarah and John from 
the clutches of the nasty Terminator. I don't really want to tell 
you anything about the film as it will only spoil it. Well, maybe 
I'll tell you a few bits. What happens is when the real baddy 
appears (played by Robert Patrick) he kills a Police officers and 
uses his clothes. His target is to kill John Connor and so he 
goes down the arcades looking for him. John sees this bloke 
looking for him and thinks that the police are after him for 
something, so he runs. The Nasty terminator runs after him and 
there is a chase down the corridor. Then John runs out through a 
door to see Arnie coming towards him with a box of flowers, which 
are disguising a large (erm..) gun. John's Under wear turns brown 
as he realises that in about 3 seconds he will be full of big 
wholes and that his body will be made up of 50% lead. Anyway he's 
stuck between the two and just as you think (or are supposed to 
think) Arnie will kill him, he tells him to duck and shoots the 
other terminator to bits. 
   When I read a review of this film it said that it was mainly 
one big running battle between the two terminators. This is not 
strictly true though and there is a bit in the middle of the film 
where the T-1000 doesn't appear for about 30 minutes. 
   I had heard so much about the FX of the T-1000 in this film 
that I was expecting something really special. And thats exactly 
what I got. For example there is one part where Arnie holds a gun 
about 2 cms away from the T-1000's head and fires. You see his 
head split right in two, but then mould back together again so 
there is no trace of where the bullet went. I did feel however 
that the ability of the Terminator to split up and build back 
together again was mainly just to show off the FX and really 
didn't have much to do with the story line. Some of the best FX 
in the film were not actullay to do with the robot. These FX were 
done when Sarah is having a dream about the future. You see 
people playing with there kids in a playground and then there is 
a massive explosion in the backround (nuclear bomb). Even though 
the bomb is miles away you see the flames engulf everyone, you 
see Sarah completely on fire as everything around her burns 
aswell. You then see lots of different shots of the city being 
blown away. Although this was probably easier to do than the 
robot, FX wise, I found it very effective indeed.
   Right, time to tell you another bit out of the film I think. 
Okay, Arnie and John are going to rescue Sarah from the looney 
bin and John is trying to explain to Arn that he should not kill 
people. Before they enter the prison John makes arnie swear not to 
kill anyone. So, they pull up out side the front gate and a 
security guard comes out and asks for some ID. Arnie, Calmly gets 
off the bike and shoot the bloke in both knee caps. John shouts 
something like "what did you do that for!", and arnie says "he'll 
live". Okay, so it isn't funny in the telling, but it did raise a 
chuckle or two in the cinema. 
   Time to compare the first and second film now. Firstly the FX 
are miles better in T2 than is T1, which is what you'd expect 
seeing as they used so much money on them. Also there is another 
ingrediant in T2, humour. About the only mildly amusing bit in 
the fist film was when Arnie said "I'll be back" and then drove 
through the front of the police station in his car. While I did 
have a giggle at most of the amusing bits in T2, I somehow 
thought that it didn't fit in with the rest of the film. Also, 
becuase everyone thought Arnie saying "I'll be back" in T1 was so 
good, they had him saying it again in this one, which didn't work 
at all.
   The Stroyline is pretty darn good I have to say, and the 
action keeps the film exciting to the end (and after). It tells 
you all the things you wanted to know after watching the first 
one, like how the wars started etc. There is still a vital 
ingrediant which the first had and the second didn't though. It 
is hard for me to explain what it is, you can only really find 
out by watching both films yourself. I think one of the best bits 
about T1 was the idea of there being something out there, it's 
only aim being to kill you, it would track you down for as long 
as it takes, you couldn't bargin with it, pay it not to kill you, 
reson with it, it was just there to find and kill you. There was 
just two humans against this thing, where ever they went the 
terminator would find them. This feeling seems to have been lost 
in T2 as there is now a Terminator on the good guys side aswell. 
Even with the odds stacked against them it just wasn't the same.
   I think I will do ratings for the original film aswell so you 
get a good comparison

RATINGS
FILM: The Terminator
GRAFICAL FX: 80% (not bad considering how old it is)
SOUNDTRACK: 92%
STORYLINE: 90% (Not as simple as it first seems)
APPEAL: 96% 
OVERALL: 96% (what can I say?)

FILM: Terminator 2: Judgemnet Day (you find out why it is called 
that in the film)
GRAFICAL FX: 96%
SOUND TRACK: 92% (similar to the first)
STORYLINE: 94% (More complex and well thought out than the first)
APPEAL (after seeing it once): 93%
OVERALL: 94%

Although I knew they could never re make a classic like 
Terminator, it was still a very excellent film and I would 
recomend you watch it as soon as you have the chance. If, for 
some reason you haven't seen T1 then watch that first!!!
   Oh yeah, I wouldn't pin too much hope on there being a third 
Terminator, I can't see how they'd ever make a viable storyline 
for it. If you wanna know why then watch T2!

